{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523005"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:51:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:51:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13864"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13864"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.56,0.05,0.01,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6481"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104572"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6481","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6481"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86901"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"6565"},{"type":"tags","id":"12910"},{"type":"tags","id":"12921"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12869"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13073"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22698"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104572"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man is admitted to hospital with acute pancreatitis and management is started with analgesics and intravenous fluid therapy. He responds well to treatment, but on day three of admission he complains of pain at his cannula site. He has a medical history of hypertension and takes amlodipine regularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable but alert. His temperature is 37.6\u00b0C, pulse rate 95/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, and SpO2 96% on room air. His chest is clear on auscultation bilaterally. His abdomen is soft with mild epigastric tenderness. There is no costovertebral angle tenderness. There is redness and mild swelling around his peripheral intravenous cannula site on his forearm (Image - note that this photo was taken a few days later in his hospital admission however the cannula was \u003Cem\u003Ein situ \u003C/em\u003Eat time of assessment).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Obtain blood and urine cultures, then start intravenous flucloxacillin","Remove the peripheral intravenous cannula and observe","Administer oral amoxicillin-clavulanate","Perform abdominal CT scan to assess for pancreatic necrosis","Start anticoagulation"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in this scenario is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eremove the peripheral intravenous cannula and observe\u003C/strong\u003E. The description of the cannula site in this case is consistent with phlebitis at the cannula site, which is a common source of hospital-acquired fever. Given there are no signs of sepsis, removing the cannula and observing the patient\u0027s response is a reasonable first step before escalating to more invasive investigations or broad-spectrum antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObtaining blood and urine cultures, then starting intravenous flucloxacillin\u003C/strong\u003E would be an overreaction at this stage. While cultures may eventually be necessary if the fever persists, starting with intravenous antibiotics is not justified based on the current clinical picture and would be an inappropriate use of this important antibiotic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering oral amoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step. While this oral \u03b2-lactam antibiotic could potentially treat a mild soft tissue infection, it is premature to start antibiotics before removing the likely source of infection (the intravenous cannula) and observing the patient\u0027s response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming an abdominal CT scan to assess for pancreatic necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not the most appropriate next step. While the patient was admitted with pancreatitis, his abdominal examination shows only mild epigastric tenderness, and there are no specific symptoms suggesting worsening pancreatitis. The obvious source of fever (intravenous cannula site) should be addressed first.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting anticoagulation\u003C/strong\u003E would be an inappropriate response at this stage as, in patients without cancer, anticoagulation is not routinely recommended for superficial thrombophlebitis associated with intravenous cannulas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the importance of careful clinical assessment of intravenous cannulation sites in hospitalised patients. Simple interventions, such as removing an infected intravenous cannula, can often resolve the issue without resorting to broad-spectrum antibiotics or excessive investigations. If a fever persists after removing the cannula, further evaluation including cultures and imaging may be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients presenting with fever, locating the source requires systematic evaluation of common infection sites and consideration of non-infectious causes.","Phlebitis at intravenous cannula sites is a common source of hospital-acquired fever and often resolves with removal of the cannula.","Broad-spectrum antibiotics should be reserved for severe presentations or when the source of infection remains unclear after initial evaluation and management."],"references":["Hadaway L. Short peripheral intravenous catheters and infections. J Infus Nurs. 2012 Jul-Aug;35(4):230-40. Available at: https://journals.lww.com/journalofinfusionnursing/abstract/2012/07000/short_peripheral_intravenous_catheters_and.7.aspx","Peripheral Intravenous catheter (PIVC) infection prevention clinical directive. At SA Health [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/b8b0b71d-899e-42aa-ac3b-ca37d905f9a8/Clinical_Directive_PIVC_Infection_Prevention_v1.0_22.11.2019.pdf?MOD=AJPERES\u0026CACHEID=ROOTWORKSPACE-b8b0b71d-899e-42aa-ac3b-ca37d905f9a8-mWhfA4q","Yuen HLA, Fang W, Tran H, Chunilal SD. Cannula provoked upper extremity superficial vein thrombophlebitis: are we overtreating? Intern Med J. 2022 Nov;52(11):1995-1997. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC9828520/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86901"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13864"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20849"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20849"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kYhTRyDkPsiLkhutD8U9SkjznT6nUG.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/kYhTRyDkPsiLkhutD8U9SkjznT6nUG.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":377}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86901","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86901"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T16:11:55+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T16:11:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6481"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104572"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","